What Is Bootloader
A bootloader is a small program that runs when you power on a computer.
Its job is to initialize hardware and load the operating system into memory so the system can start.
Without a bootloader, your machine wouldn‚Äôt know how to transition from firmware (BIOS/UEFI) into the OS.

Grub
Grub Is A Default Bootloader For Triaxis

Efistub
On Triaxis, you don‚Äôt ‚Äúinstall‚Äù EFISTUB as a package ‚Äî it‚Äôs already built into the Linux kernel.
What you do is configure your UEFI firmware to boot the kernel directly (without GRUB) by creating a boot entry that points to the kernel and initrd using efibootmgr.

1. Verify Kernel Support
Ubuntu kernels (since 12.10) include EFI stub loader support by default.

No extra installation is required ‚Äî the kernel itself can be loaded directly by UEFI.

2. Identify EFI Partition
Check your EFI System Partition (ESP), usually mounted at /boot/efi.

Run:

bash
lsblk | grep EFI
or check /etc/fstab for the ESP mount point.

3. Copy Kernel & Initrd
Ubuntu/Triaxis places kernel and initrd in /boot.

Example:

Kernel: /boot/vmlinuz-<version>

Initrd: /boot/initrd.img-<version>

4. Create EFISTUB Boot Entry
Use efibootmgr to register the kernel as a boot option:

bash
sudo efibootmgr -c -d /dev/sda -p 1 \
  -L "Ubuntu EFISTUB" \
  -l '\vmlinuz-<version>' \
  -u "root=/dev/sdaX ro initrd=\initrd.img-<version>"
-d /dev/sda ‚Üí disk containing EFI partition

-p 1 ‚Üí partition number of EFI System Partition

-L ‚Üí label for the boot entry

-l ‚Üí path to kernel relative to EFI partition

-u ‚Üí kernel command line (root device, initrd, etc.)

5. Confirm Entry
Run:

bash
sudo efibootmgr -v
You should see ‚ÄúUbuntu EFISTUB‚Äù listed as a boot option.

6. Reboot & Test
Restart your system and select the new EFISTUB entry from the UEFI boot menu. If configured correctly, Ubuntu should boot directly without GRUB.

‚ö†Ô∏è Risks & Considerations
No boot menu: EFISTUB boots straight into the kernel. If you need multiple kernels or OSes, GRUB/systemd-boot may be more flexible.

Kernel updates: Each time Ubuntu updates the kernel, you must update the EFISTUB entry manually.

Recovery: Keep GRUB installed as a fallback in case EFISTUB fails.

Limine

install Limine on Triaxis, you need to build it from source,
copy its bootloader files to your EFI System Partition (ESP),
and configure a limine.cfg file. Limine is not available in Ubuntu‚Äôs repositories or TUR Triaxis User Repository, so manual installation is required.

1. Install Build Dependencies
sudo apt update
sudo apt install build-essential git mtools

2. Clone Limine Source
git clone https://github.com/limine-bootloader/limine.git
cd limine

3. Build Limine
Compile the bootloader with make

4 Prepare EFI System Partition
Identify your EFI partition (usually /boot/efi).
Mount it if not already mounted:
sudo mount /dev/sdX1 /boot/efi

5 Install Limine Bootloader
Run
sudo ./limine-install /dev/sdX

6 Create Configuration File
Limine uses limine.cfg for boot entries. Example:

TIMEOUT=5
DEFAULT_ENTRY=Triaxis

:Triaxis
    PROTOCOL=linux
    KERNEL_PATH=/boot/vmlinuz-<version>
    INITRD_PATH=/boot/initrd.img-<version>
    CMDLINE=root=/dev/sdaX ro quiet splash

7 Update UEFI Boot Entries (Optional)
You can register Limine with efibootmgr
sudo efibootmgr -c -d /dev/sdX -p 1 -L "Limine Bootloader" -l '\EFI\BOOT\BOOTX64.EFI'

8 Reboot Your System

Systemd Boot

Systemd-boot only works with UEFI systems. Check with:
[ -d /sys/firmware/efi ] && echo "UEFI system" || echo "Legacy BIOS"

Remove GRUB (Optional but Recommended)
If you want to fully replace GRUB:
sudo apt purge --allow-remove-essential grub2-common grub-pc-bin grub-pc grub-efi-amd64-bin grub-efi-amd64-signed grub-common os-prober shim-signed
sudo apt autoremove --purge
sudo rm -rf /boot/grub /boot/efi/EFI/ubuntu

3. Install systemd-boot
sudo apt install systemd-boot systemd-ukify

4 Configure Kernel Command Line
Create /etc/kernel/cmdline with your desired boot parameters. Example:
root=/dev/sdaX ro quiet splash
You can check your current parameters with:
cat /proc/cmdline

5 Hook for Kernel Updates
Create a script /etc/kernel/postinst.d/zz-update-systemd-boot
#!/bin/bash
kernel-install add "$1" "/boot/vmlinuz-$1"

Make it executable:
sudo chmod 755 /etc/kernel/postinst.d/zz-update-systemd-boot

6 Reinstall Kernel to Trigger Setup
  sudo apt reinstall linux-image-$(uname -r)

7 Reboot

Risks & Considerations
Kernel updates: Unlike GRUB, systemd-boot requires hooks/scripts to keep entries updated.

Dual-boot setups: It‚Äôs simpler but less feature-rich than GRUB for managing multiple OSes.

Fallback: Keep a GRUB rescue USB or live Ubuntu installer in case of misconfiguration.

syslinux

Install Syslinux Packages
Triaxis provides Syslinux in its repositories:
sudo apt update
sudo apt install syslinux syslinux-common

Prepare Target Partition
Syslinux works on FAT filesystems (FAT16/FAT32).

Format your target device (USB stick or partition):

bash
sudo mkfs.vfat /dev/sdX1
Replace /dev/sdX1 with your partition.

Mount it:

bash
sudo mount /dev/sdX1 /mnt
Install Syslinux Bootloader
Run:

bash
sudo syslinux --install /dev/sdX1
This writes the Syslinux boot sector and places ldlinux.sys in the root of the FAT partition.

Copy Kernel & Initrd
Place your Linux kernel and initrd files onto the partition:

bash
sudo cp /boot/vmlinuz-$(uname -r) /mnt/
sudo cp /boot/initrd.img-$(uname -r) /mnt/
Create Configuration File
Syslinux uses syslinux.cfg in the root of the partition. Example:

ini
DEFAULT linux
LABEL linux
    KERNEL /vmlinuz-<version>
    INITRD /initrd.img-<version>
    APPEND root=/dev/sdaX ro quiet splash
Adjust <version> and root device accordingly.

Unmount & Test
Unmount the partition:

bash
sudo umount /mnt
Reboot and select the device in your firmware boot menu. Syslinux should load and present your configured entry.

‚ö†Ô∏è Risks & Considerations
FAT-only: Syslinux requires FAT filesystems; it won‚Äôt install on ext4 directly.

Manual upkeep: Kernel updates require you to copy new kernel/initrd files and update syslinux.cfg.

Fallback: Keep GRUB or another bootloader available for recovery.

UEFI vs BIOS: Syslinux is primarily BIOS-oriented; for UEFI, consider Syslinux EFI or alternatives like systemd-boot

Windows Boot Manager

You can add Triaxis to the Windows Boot Manager so that when your PC starts,
you‚Äôll see Triaxis listed alongside Windows.
This is typically done using the Windows Boot Manager (BCD) and a tool like EasyBCD,
or by manually configuring entries with bcdedit.

Method 1: Using EasyBCD (Simplest)
Install EasyBCD on Windows (free for non-commercial use).

Open EasyBCD ‚Üí Add New Entry.

Select Linux/BSD ‚Üí choose GRUB2 (Ubuntu uses GRUB2).

Point it to the partition where Ubuntu is installed.

Save settings ‚Üí reboot.

You‚Äôll now see Ubuntu listed in the Windows Boot Manager menu.

üîß Method 2: Using bcdedit (Manual)
Boot into Windows.

Open Command Prompt as Administrator.

Find your EFI partition (usually mounted as \EFI\ubuntu\grubx64.efi).

Ubuntu installer places GRUB EFI files there.

Add a new boot entry:

cmd
bcdedit /create /d "Ubuntu" /application bootsector
Note the identifier returned (e.g., {abcd-1234}), then link it to the GRUB EFI file:

cmd
bcdedit /set {abcd-1234} device partition=\Device\HarddiskVolumeX
bcdedit /set {abcd-1234} path \EFI\ubuntu\grubx64.efi
bcdedit /displayorder {abcd-1234} /addlast
Reboot ‚Üí Windows Boot Manager will now list Ubuntu.

‚ö†Ô∏è Things to Keep in Mind
UEFI vs BIOS: On UEFI systems, Ubuntu usually registers itself automatically in the firmware boot menu. Adding it to Windows Boot Manager is optional.

Updates: Kernel or GRUB updates in Ubuntu don‚Äôt affect the Windows Boot Manager entry, but if EFI paths change, you may need to reconfigure.

Fallback: Keep a live USB handy in case boot entries break.

Dualboot
Dual‚Äëbooting Triaxis GNU/Linux with Windows and other operating systems is essentially about managing your firmware (UEFI/BIOS), partitions, and bootloader so each OS can coexist without overwriting the others.

Step‚Äëby‚ÄëStep Dual‚ÄëBoot

1. Prepare Your Disk
Back up first ‚Äî partitioning always carries risk.

Use Windows‚Äô Disk Management or gparted from a live Linux USB to shrink existing partitions and create free space for Triaxis and any other OS.

Plan partitions:

One EFI System Partition (ESP) ‚Äî already exists if Windows is UEFI.

Separate root partitions for each OS (e.g., / for Triaxis, / for Ubuntu, etc.).

Optional: shared data partition (NTFS or exFAT) for cross‚ÄëOS access.

2. Install Windows First (if not already)
Windows tends to overwrite bootloaders. Installing it first ensures later OSes can reclaim control.

3. Install Triaxis GNU/Linux
Boot from the Triaxis installer USB.

Choose manual partitioning and install into the prepared partition.

Install the bootloader (GRUB, Limine, or systemd‚Äëboot depending on your ritual) into the EFI System Partition.

Ensure the installer doesn‚Äôt overwrite Windows partitions.

4. Add Other OSes (Ubuntu, BSD, etc.)
Repeat the process: boot installer, select manual partitioning, install into its own partition.

Each OS will attempt to add itself to the EFI boot menu.

5. Manage the Bootloader
GRUB (default choice):

Detects Windows and other OSes automatically.

Run sudo update-grub inside Triaxis/Ubuntu to refresh entries.

systemd‚Äëboot or Limine:

Requires manual config files (loader.conf, limine.cfg).

Add entries for each kernel and for Windows Boot Manager (EFI/Microsoft/Boot/bootmgfw.efi).

6. Verify UEFI Boot Entries
Use efibootmgr in Linux or bcdedit in Windows to check entries.

Example for Windows entry in GRUB:

bash
sudo update-grub
GRUB should list ‚ÄúWindows Boot Manager‚Äù automatically.

7. Reboot & Test
On startup, you should see your chosen bootloader menu.

Select Triaxis, Windows, or other OS as desired.

‚ö†Ô∏è Key Considerations
UEFI vs BIOS: Modern systems use UEFI. Stick to one mode across all OSes.

Kernel updates: GRUB handles them automatically; systemd‚Äëboot/Limine require manual edits.

Rescue USB: Always keep a live USB handy in case boot entries break.

Shared lore: If you want a unified archive, consider a shared /home or data partition accessible across OSes.

Lilo

Install The Bootloader Using
sudo apt install lilo
sudo lilo

Config file: /etc/lilo.conf
Notes: Works only with BIOS systems, not UEFI. Rarely used today, but symbolic as a ‚Äúphantom mask‚Äù in your lore.

rEFInd

sudo apt install refind
sudo refind-install

Clover

No native Linux package; you must download Clover EFI binaries and copy them to the EFI System Partition.

Process:

Mount ESP (/boot/efi).

Copy Clover EFI files into /EFI/CLOVER/.

Add entry with efibootmgr.

U‚ÄëBoot (Das U‚ÄëBoot)

Not typical on desktop Linux. You cross‚Äëcompile U‚ÄëBoot for your hardware:

git clone https://source.denx.de/u-boot/u-boot.git
cd u-boot
make <board_defconfig>
make

Barebox

git clone https://github.com/barebox/barebox.git
cd barebox
make <board_defconfig>
make

